'''Mahmoud Ahmed Ibrahim Hassan''' ({{langx|ar|محمود أحمد إبراهيم حسن}}; born 1 October 1994), commonly known as '''Trézéguet''' ({{langx|ar|تريزيجيه|links=no}}),<ref name="2018-espn-name" /> is an Egyptian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left winger]] for [[Egyptian Premier League]] club [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] and the [[Egypt national football team|Egypt national team]]. His nickname is taken from the French former footballer [[David Trezeguet]], after his former youth coach noticed similarities of playing style and appearance between the pair.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ahmed |first=Saher |date=27 January 2025 |title=OFFICIAL: Al Ahly Secure Surprise Signing of Trezeguet |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2025/01/27/official-al-ahly-secure-surprise-signing-of-trezeguet/ |access-date=28 January 2025 |website=KingFut}}</ref>

Trézéguet began his career with Al Ahly, breaking into the first team at the age of 18 and helping them win the [[2012 CAF Champions League]] and [[2013 CAF Champions League]]. In 2015, he joined Belgian team [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]], and the move was later made permanent. However, he struggled to establish himself in the first team and spent the following two seasons on loan, first with fellow Belgian side [[Royal Excel Mouscron|Mouscron]] and later Turkish side [[Kasımpaşa S.K.|Kasımpaşa]]. With Kasımpaşa, he became the highest scoring Egyptian player in the Turkish top flight in a single season which prompted the club to make the transfer permanent in 2018.

Having represented Egypt at [[Egypt national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Egypt national under-23 football team|under-23]] level, Trézéguet made his full debut for the Egyptian senior side in 2014 at the age of 19 in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]]. He was named in Egypt's squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], playing in all three group matches. To date, he has made over 80 appearances for his country's national team, scoring 22 goals.

==Club career==

===Al Ahly===
Born in [[Kafr El Sheikh]] governorate,<ref name="Soccerway"/> he was given the nickname ''Trézéguet'' at age nine by Badr Ragab, a youth coach at his school team, when he noticed that Mahmoud had a shaved head and a clinical goal-scoring instinct that heavily resembled the French [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] winner and [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] legend, [[David Trezeguet]]. The coach used it to motivate him to become an international star, and the name stuck with him for the rest of his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/06/22/mahmoud-trezeguet-people-used-to-think-im-french-because-of-my-name/ |title=Mahmoud Trezeguet: People used to think I'm French because of my name |website=KingFut.com |author=Ahmed El Ramady |date=22 June 2018 |access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/trezeguet-aston-villa-mahmoud-hassan-16521905 |title=This is why Aston Villa transfer target Mahmoud Hassan is called 'Trezeguet' |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |author=Alex Dicken |date=11 July 2019 |access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref> Playing as a striker, he joined the youth academy at [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] after turning down an offer to move to Qatar. He soon converted to playing as a midfielder in the youth academy following the advice of coach Ali Maher.<ref name="kfprofile">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2013/06/14/player-profile-mahmoud-trezeguet-hassan/ |title=Player Profile: Mahmoud Hassan Trezeguet |website=KingFut.com |author=Mohamed Farouk |date=14 June 2013 |access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> After being promoted to the senior squad by manager [[Manuel José de Jesus]], on the advice of Maher, he made his professional debut in the [[2012 CAF Champions League]] as a substitute in place of [[Mohamed Aboutrika]] in a match against [[Cairo derby|local]] rivals [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]. Jesus later described him as "one of the best youngsters he's ever came across."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/10/30/trezeguet-gamal-were-close-leaving-alahly/ |title=Aly Maher: Trezeguet, Gamal were close to leaving Al Ahly |website=KingFut.com |author=Malak Hassouna |date=30 October 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He made his first start for Al Ahly later in the competition against Ghanaian side [[Berekum Chelsea F.C.|Berekum Chelsea]]. Al Ahly went on to win the Champions League although Trézéguet did not feature in the [[2012 CAF Champions League Final|final]].<ref name="kfprofile"/>

In April 2013, he was offered a trial for French side [[OGC Nice|Nice]] after establishing himself in the first team at eighteen and playing in the U20 [[African Youth Championship|African Youth Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Ahly's promising midfielder set for trial at Nice |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/6/51/69414/Sports/Egyptian-Football/Ahlys-promising-midfielder-set-for-trial-at-Nice-.aspx |access-date=23 May 2016 |work=[[Al-Ahram]] English |date=16 April 2013}}</ref> postponing the trial for a later date to help Al Ahly during an injury crisis that left them short of first team players.<ref name="kfprofile"/>

He was later offered a trial with English side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] but the club pulled out of a potential loan transfer with an option to buy after being unable to meet Al Ahly's valuation,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2013/07/27/nottingham-forest-end-pursuit-of-egypts-trezeguet/ |title=Nottingham Forest end pursuit of Egypt's Mahmoud 'Trezeguet' |website=KingFut.com |date=27 July 2013 |access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> stated at [[Pound sterling|£1]] million by Al Ahly's director of football Sayed Abdel-Hafiz.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2013/12/23/al-ahly-nottingham-forest-can-mahmoud-hassan-trezeguet-one-million-pounds/ |title=Al Ahly: Forest can have Mahmoud Hassan Trezeguet for £1million |website=KingFut.com |author=Marwan Ahmed |date=23 December 2013 |access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> In December 2013, he was linked with Scottish club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], who saw a bid of £420,000 rejected.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bath |first1=Richard |title=Richard Bath: Celtic may suit Egyptian Trezeguet |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/richard-bath-celtic-may-suit-egyptian-trezeguet-1-3256252 |access-date=23 May 2016 |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=5 January 2014}}</ref> However, he later ended speculation over his future by stating his intention to remain with Al Ahly until at least the end of the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2014/02/06/mahmoud-hassan-trezeguet-talks-al-ahlys-official-site/ |title=Celtic target Mahmoud Trezeguet: Al Ahly are my focus, I postponed the idea of going to other clubs |website=KingFut.com |author=Nouran Hegazy |date=6 February 2014 |access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> In January 2015, he won the Best Egypt-based Player Award at the annual Youth and Sports Broadcasting annual gala.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/01/23/best-footballers-egypt-annual-awards-gala/ |title=Cairo giants' stars named best footballers in Egypt at annual awards gala |author=Mohamed Osama |date=23 January 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

After helping Al Ahly win the [[Egyptian Premier League]] title in the 2014–15 season,<ref name="Soccerway">{{Soccerway|253078|access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> speculation over his future arose again after it was confirmed that they would "listen to offers" as the club began to experience financial difficulties<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/04/29/exclusive-alahly-listen-trezeguet-offers/ |title=Al Ahly will listen to Trezeguet offers |website=KingFut.com |author=Marwan Ahmed |date=29 April 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> The end of his season was disrupted after being ruled out for six weeks with a dislocated shoulder suffered during a 2–1 defeat to Tunisian side [[Club Africain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/05/18/mahmoud-trezeguet-ruled-6-weeks/ |title=Al Ahly midfielder Trezeguet ruled out for six weeks |website=KingFut.com |author=Mohamed Salama |date=18 May 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

===Anderlecht===
[[File:Mahmoud Trezeguet in Anderlecht.jpg|upright|thumb|200px|Trézéguet with [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] in 2016]]

Despite Al Ahly director of football [[Wael Gomaa]] stating his desire for Trézéguet to remain with the club, describing him as "one of the main elements of the team",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/06/16/al-ahly-technical-staff-want-trezeguet-to-stay-amid-anderlecht-interest/ |title=Al Ahly technical staff want Trezeguet to stay amid Anderlecht interest |website=KingFut.com |author=Salma Abdallah |date=16 June 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> on 6 August 2015, Trézéguet joined Belgian side [[RSC Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] on loan for a fee of €1&nbsp;million, with Anderlecht gaining an option to sign him on a permanent basis after the season-long loan for a further €2.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/08/06/official-trezeguet-completes-anderlecht-move/ |title=Trezeguet completes Anderlecht move from Al Ahly |author=Mohaned Ghanem |website=KingFut.com |date=6 August 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> His arrival at the club was disrupted by a broken shoulder sustained while training with his national team in the United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/10/07/trezeguet-out-for-weeks-shoulder-injury/ |title=Trezeguet out for at least six weeks following shoulder injury |website=KingFut.com |author=Marwan Ibrahim |date=7 October 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> ruling him out for several months after being forced to undergo surgery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/10/14/egypts-trezeguet-undergo-shoulder-surgery-several-months/ |title=Egypt's Trezeguet to undergo shoulder surgery, out for several months |website=KingFut.com |author=Malak Hassouna |date=14 October 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> Anderlecht manager [[Besnik Hasi]] stated his disappointment in the disruption of the loan spell and admitted that it had been difficult for the club to analyse Trézéguet's ability.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/10/20/bensik-hasi-trezeguet-problems-dont-stop/ |title=Anderlecht manager Hasi: Trezeguet's problems don't stop |website=KingFut.com |author=Khaled Ali |date=20 October 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

Trézéguet returned to training in early December 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/12/09/mahomud-trezeguet-rejoins-anderlecht-training/ |title=Mahmoud Trezeguet rejoins Anderlecht training |website=KingFut.com |date=9 December 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> before making his competitive debut for Anderlecht on 27 December 2015 in a 2–1 victory over [[K.V.C. Westerlo|Westerlo]] when he replaced [[Dodi Lukebakio]] in the 82nd minute.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trézéguet makes Anderlecht debut in close win |url=http://www.kingfut.com/2015/12/27/trezeguet-anderlecht-debut-win/ |website=KingFut.com |access-date=6 July 2016 |date=27 December 2015}}</ref> Following his debut, Hasi described him as having "great ability and the speed, and I can see a bright future for him."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2015/12/29/hasi-trezguet-needs-to-prove-what-he-is-worth/ |title=Hasi: Trezeguet needs to prove his worth |website=KingFut.com |author=Khaled Ali |date=29 December 2015 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He made his first start for the club a month later in a 2–0 defeat to [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/01/17/trezeguet-full-debut-anderlecht-gent/ |title=Trezeguet makes full debut for Anderlecht away to Gent |website=KingFut.com |author=James Sibeleki |date=17 January 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> However, he was dropped from the side soon after with Hasi claiming that the language barrier was making it difficult for Trézéguet to understand the team's tactics, commenting "He is a diligent player and trains well with us so [...] but he rarely understands what we say,"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/02/18/hasi-trezeguet-lacks-language/ |title=Hasi: Trezeguet is talented but lacks language |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=18 February 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> and that he was no longer considered the star player of the team as he had been with Al Ahly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/02/22/hasi-comments-on-trezeguet-situation/ |title=Besnik Hasi: Trezeguet was the star at Al Ahly |website=KingFut.com |author=Fatma Abusief |date=22 February 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

In March 2016, Anderlecht announced they were considering exercising their option to sign Trézéguet permanently from [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] for a reported transfer fee of €2.2&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite news |title=Van Holsbeeck: "On garde Trezeguet !" |url=http://www.dhnet.be/sports/football/division-1a/anderlecht/van-holsbeeck-on-garde-trezeguet-56e71fbb35708ea2d38dc2a6 |access-date=7 July 2016 |work=[[La Dernière Heure]] |date=15 March 2016 |language=fr}}</ref> despite only making seven league appearances in his first season. In May the move was completed,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mahmoud Trézéguet signs Anderlecht contract |url=http://www.kingfut.com/2016/05/19/mahmoud-trezeguet-signs-anderlecht-contract/ |website=KingFut.com |access-date=7 July 2016 |date=19 May 2016}}</ref> with Trézéguet becoming the second most expensive sale in Al Ahly's history after [[Flávio Amado]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/05/13/trezeguet-join-anderlecht-permanently/ |title=Official: Trezeguet joins Anderlecht permanently |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=13 May 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

====Loan to Mouscron====
He enjoyed a prolific pre-season prior to the 2016–17 season, scoring four times, earning praise from new manager [[René Weiler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/07/22/anderlecht-trezeguet-special/ |title=Anderlecht manager: Trezeguet is a special player |website=KingFut.com |author=Abdelrahman Aboelnoor |date=22 July 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> However, the signing of [[Nicolae Stanciu (footballer, born 1993)|Nicolae Stanciu]] prompted the club to offer Trézéguet out on loan to gain playing time,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/08/30/rsca-mouscron-peruwelz-trezeguet-loan/ |title=Mouscron-Péruwelz set to sign Trezeguet on loan from Anderlecht |website=KingFut.com |author=Abdelrahman Amr |date=30 August 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> eventually joining fellow Belgian side [[Royal Excel Mouscron]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/08/31/mouscron-egypt-trezeguet-loan/ |title=Mouscron sign Egypt's Trezeguet on season-long loan |website=KingFut.com |author=Mahmoud Khaled |date=31 August 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> In his first seven appearances for the club, he was directly involved in five goals, scoring two and assisting three including a solo effort against Gent after starting a run from inside his own half,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/10/15/video-trezeguet-scores-incredible-solo-goal-in-draw-against-genk/ |title=Trezeguet scores incredible solo goal in draw against Genk |website=KingFut.com |author=Robert Malit |date=15 October 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> leading manager [[Glen De Boeck]] to label him the "most talented player in our team."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/10/28/trezeguet-talented-player-team/ |title=Mouscron coach: Trezeguet most talented player in our team |website=KingFut.com |author=Adham Mira |date=28 October 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

Mouscron became embroiled in a relegation battle but Trézéguet gained praise for his performances from Anderlecht coach Jean-Francois Lenvain, who continued working with him during his loan spell,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/12/01/anderlecht-coach-trezeguet-ideveloping-well-away-spotlight/ |title=Anderlecht coach: Trezeguet is developing well away from the spotlight |website=KingFut.com |author=Ossama Mohamed |date=1 December 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> and led former Anderlecht player [[Wim De Coninck]] to call for Trézéguet to be recalled by Anderlecht to replace Stanciu, remarking "If he (Trézéguet) had the amount of chances Stanciu has now he'd be in a different place."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2016/12/01/coninck-trezeguet-return-andrelecht/ |title=Wim De Coninck believes Trezeguet must return to Anderlecht |website=KingFut.com |author=Youssef Wael |date=1 December 2016 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> In the final match of the season, Trézéguet scored the opening goal of a 2–0 victory over [[K.V. Kortrijk|KV Kortrijk]] that saw Mouscron overtake [[K.V.C. Westerlo|Westerlo]] to avoid relegation from the [[Belgian First Division A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/03/12/trezeguet-goal-helps-mouscron-avoid-relegation/ |title=Trézéguet's early goal helps Mouscron avoid relegation |website=KinhFut.com |author=Mazin Rizk |date=12 March 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> After featuring in the Europa League playoffs, he returned to Anderlecht at the end of his loan spell having scored seven goals during 28 appearances in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/05/16/mahmoud-trezeguet-mouscron-loan-expires/ |title=Mahmoud Trezeguet leaves Mouscron after loan expires |website=KingFut.com |date=16 May 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> Prior to his return, it was reported that Anderlecht intended to sell Trézéguet due to manager Wilder deeming him "not tactically disciplined",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/04/15/anderlecht-sell-trezeguet-reports/ |title=Anderlecht to sell 'not tactically disciplined' Trezeguet – Reports |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=15 April 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> an opinion supported by Mouscron manager [[Mircea Rednic]] who commented "he runs in every part of the pitch except the part we need him to go to."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/04/17/rednic-trezeguet-tactical-discipline/ |title=Rednic: Trezeguet needs to work on his tactical discipline |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=17 April 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

===Kasımpaşa===
After returning to Anderlecht, Trézéguet was linked with transfers to Turkish side [[Galatasaray S.K.|Galatasaray]] and his former club Al Ahly and even considered terminating his contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/06/14/report-galatasaray-interested-trezeguet/ |title=Report: Galatasaray interested in Trezeguet |website=KingFut.com |author=Ahmed Wagih |date=14 June 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/06/16/exclusive-trezeguet-considers-terminating-anderlecht-contract/ |title=Trezeguet considers terminating Anderlecht contract |website=KingFut.com |author=Marwan Ahmed |date=16 June 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He eventually joined Turkish side [[Kasımpaşa S.K.|Kasımpaşa]] on a season-long loan deal with the club having the option to make the move permanent for €2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/07/05/official-trezeguet-completes-move-turkish-club-kasimpasa/ |title=Trezeguet completes move to Turkish club Kasimpasa |website=KingFut.com |author=Serge Nasri |date=5 July 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on the opening day of the 2017–18 season, scoring the opening goal of a 3–1 victory over [[Alanyaspor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/08/13/trezeguet-scores-kasimpasa-opener/ |title=Trezeguet impresses as Kasimpasa beat Alanyaspor in league opener |website=KingFut.com |author=Ramez Nathan |date=13 August 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He scored five goals in his first twelve appearances for Kasımpaşa, including a brace against [[Akhisar Belediyespor]] in the [[Turkish Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/10/24/trezeguet-scores-brace-kasimpasa-cup/ |title=Trezeguet scores brace, assists as Kasimpasa thrash Belediyespor in Cup |website=KingFut.com |author=Salma Abdallah |date=24 October 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> before his run in the first team was interrupted following a three match ban he received after being sent off in a match against [[Bursaspor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2017/11/18/trezeguet-banned-red-card-bursaspor/ |title=Trezeguet banned for three games after red card against Bursaspor |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=17 November 2017 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

On his return, Trézéguet surpassed his previous career high goalscoring record for a single season after scoring his ninth goal on 4 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/02/04/trezeguet-best-ever-tally-season/ |title=Trezeguet surpasses best-ever goal tally in a season |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=4 February 2018 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> His tenth goal of the season, scored in the club's following match against [[Yeni Malatyaspor]], saw him become only the seventh Egyptian player to reach double figures in a European league and also saw him surpass [[Ahmed Hassan (footballer, born 1975)|Ahmed Hassan]]'s record for the most goals scored by an Egyptian player in the Turkish top flight.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/02/10/trezeguet-scoring-goals-offers/ |title=I want to score more goals, says Mahmoud Trezeguet |website=KingFut.com |author=Youssef Wael |date=10 February 2018 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/03/02/trezeguet-breaks-hassan-record/ |title=Mahmoud 'Trezeguet' breaks Ahmed Hassan's record in Turkey |website=KingFut.com |author=Sina Isaac |date=2 March 2018 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> His performances saw the club activate their clause to make his transfer permanent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/04/12/kasimpasa-trigger-trezeguet-relase-clause/ |title=Kasimpasa activate Mahmoud Trezeguet's release clause |website=KingFut.com |author=Muhammad Sayed |date=12 April 2018 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

Despite signing permanently with the club in April, Trézéguet was subject to several transfer offers during the 2018 summer transfer window. He held talks with representatives of fellow Turkish side [[Galatasaray S.K.|Galatasaray]] while attending a national team training camp in Italy,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/06/03/report-galatasaray-went-to-egypt-camp-in-italy-to-meet-with-trezeguet/amp/ |title=Galatasaray went to Egypt camp in Italy to meet with Trezeguet |website=KingFut.com |author=Serge Nasri |access-date=13 July 2018}}</ref> later describing the club as his preferred destination.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/07/03/trezeguet-hopes-galatasaray-inter/ |title=Trezeguet hopes to join Galatasaray, denies confirming Inter move |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=3 July 2018 |access-date=13 July 2018}}</ref> A move to Italian side [[Inter Milan]] collapsed after the club stalled on completing the deal. The deal was to include spending the first year on loan with fellow [[Serie A]] side [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] due to Milan already reaching their foreign player quota for the upcoming season.<ref name="future">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/07/11/trezeguet-kasimpasa-future/ |title=Trezeguet releases statement on Kasimpasa future |website=KingFut.com |author=Salma Abdallah |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> A deal was later agreed with Czech side [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]], after the side met his €5&nbsp;million release clause, but was placed on hold by Trézéguet despite personal terms being agreed and the player passing a medical.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/07/11/update-trezeguet-puts-slavia-praha-move-on-hold/ |title=Trezeguet puts Slavia Praha move on hold |website=KingFut.com |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/07/11/kasimpasa-chairman-trezeguets-transfer-was-out-of-our-hands/ |title=Kasimpasa chairman: Trezeguet's transfer was out of our hands |website=KingFut.com |author=Ahmed El Ramady |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=18 July 2018}}</ref> The transfer was eventually cancelled with Trézéguet declaring his desire to remain with Kasımpaşa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/07/18/kasimpasa-mahmoud-trezeguet-stay-club/ |title=Kasimpasa confirm Mahmoud Trezeguet wants to stay at the club |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=18 July 2018 |access-date=18 July 2018}}</ref> His performances during the 2017–18 season saw him nominated for the [[Süper Lig]] Player of the Year award, losing out to [[Bafétimbi Gomis]].<ref name="POY">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/09/12/mahmoud-trezeguet-poty-bafetimbi-gomis/ |title=Mahmoud Trezeguet loses Player of the Year award to Bafetimbi Gomis |website=KingFut.com |author=Seif Soliman |date=12 September 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref>

===Aston Villa===
On 24 July 2019, Trézéguet joined [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] for a fee of £8.75&nbsp;million,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49058830 |title=Trezeguet: Aston Villa sign Egyptian winger for £8.75m |date=24 July 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref> subject to work visa and international clearance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transfer news: Aston Villa sign Trezeguet |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/News/2019/07/24/trezeguet-signs-for-aston-villa |publisher=Aston Villa F.C. |access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref> He made his debut on 10 August in a 3–1 loss away to [[Tottenham Hotspur]], playing the first 59 minutes before being substituted for fellow new signing and debutante [[Jota (Spanish footballer)|Jota]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnston |first1=Neil |title=Tottenham Hotspur 3&ndash;1 Aston Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49215981 |access-date=29 February 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2019}}</ref> Three weeks later, he was sent off in the 54th minute as Villa lost 1–0 at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oludare |first1=Shina |title=Trezeguet sets unwanted record in Aston Villa's defeat to Crystal Palace |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/trezeguet-sets-unwanted-record-in-aston-villas-defeat-to-crystal-/qhev83aftujz1lugg3795rrta |access-date=29 February 2020 |publisher=Goal |date=31 August 2019}}</ref>

Trézéguet scored his first goal for Aston Villa on 2 November 2019, in a 2–1 defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50190998 |title=Aston Villa 1–2 Liverpool |date=2 November 2019 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His performance in that game earned plaudits from national football pundits, such as [[Ian Wright]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/best-performance-pundit-prediction-aston-17194604 |title='Best performance' – The pundit prediction Aston Villa fans will love after Liverpool defeat |last=Jackson |first=Elliott |date=4 November 2019 |work=Birmingham Mail}}</ref> On 28 January 2020, he scored an injury time winner in an [[EFL Cup]] semi-final against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], to send Villa to their first final in the tournament since 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2020/01/28/trezeguet-sends-aston-villa-on-to-wembley-in-carabao-cup/|title=Trezeguet sends Aston Villa on to Wembley in Carabao Cup|last=Bonn|first=Kyle|date=28 January 2020|work=NBC Sport|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>

Trezeguet played a key role in Aston Villa's strong run of form in their final 4 games of the season, scoring 3 crucial goals against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] to help them achieve Premier League survival.

On 30 November 2020, Trézéguet suffered a severe facial injury during a Premier League defeat to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=30 November 2020|title=تريزيجيه يتعرض لإصابة قوية فى الوجه خلال مواجهة وست هام وأستون فيلا.. صور|work=Youm7|url=https://www.youm7.com/story/2020/11/30/تريزيجيه-يتعرض-لإصابة-قوية-فى-الوجه-خلال-مواجهة-وست-هام/5092874|access-date=13 January 2021|language=ar}}</ref> Shortly after recovering from that injury, but before featuring in another Villa game, Trézéguet suffered a [[hamstring]] injury which was expected to keep him sidelined for a month.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wilson|first=Amie|date=1 January 2021|title=Barkley, Mings, Trezeguet - Aston Villa injury news ahead of Manchester United|work=Birmingham Mail|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aston-villa-injury-man-united-18896713|access-date=13 January 2021}}</ref> On 13 January 2021, Trézéguet revealed on his [[Twitter]] account that he had recovered from the hamstring injury, but had now tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and was forced to isolate at home.<ref>{{Cite web|date=13 January 2021|title=Trezeguet on Twitter (In Arabic)|url=https://twitter.com/Trezeguet/status/1349038227680862208|access-date=13 January 2021|website=[[Twitter]]}}</ref> He was finally able to make his return to the first team as a late substitute in a 2–0 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 23 January 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wilson|first=Scott|date=23 January 2021|title=Match Ratings: Aston Villa 2 Newcastle United 0|work=The Northern Echo|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/19034563.match-ratings-aston-villa-2-newcastle-united-0/|access-date=25 January 2021}}</ref>

On 10 April 2021, Trézéguet suffered another injury setback, suffering a torn [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|ACL]] after a challenge from [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]] in a 2–1 away defeat to Liverpool. The injury was expected to end the [[2020–21 Aston Villa F.C. season|2020–21]] season for Trézéguet at a minimum.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ismail|first=Ali|date=11 April 2021|title=Trezeguet out for remainder of the season with ACL injury|work=KingFUT|url=https://www.kingfut.com/2021/04/11/trezeguet-reported-acl-injury/|access-date=11 April 2021}}</ref> He returned to the first team on 2 January 2022, in a 2–1 away defeat to [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], in which he received criticism for appearing to simulate contact with [[Saman Ghoddos]] in order to try and win a penalty.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Tong|first=Kobe|date=2 January 2022|title=Villa's Trezeguet is being slammed for one of the worst 'dives' that fans have ever seen|url=https://www.givemesport.com/1811617-brentford-21-aston-villa-trezeguet-slammed-for-embarrassing-dive-in-premier-league-loss|access-date=27 January 2022|website=GiveMeSport|language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== Loan to İstanbul Başakşehir ====
On 8 February 2022, Trézéguet joined [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.|İstanbul Başakşehir]] on loan until the end of the season, in a bid to get more game time and improve his fitness.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=8 February 2022|title=Trézéguet joins İstanbul Başakşehir on loan|url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2022/february/08/tr-z-guet-joins--stanbul-ba-ak-ehir-on-loan/|access-date=8 February 2022|website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref> He made his debut for Başakşehir on 12 February 2022, in a 2–0 victory over [[Gaziantep F.K.|Gaziantep]], in which he provided an assist for [[Pizzi (Portuguese footballer)|Pizzi]]'s opening goal.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Basaksehir - Gaziantep 2:0|url=https://www.flashscore.co.uk/match/vBXgtnGC/#match-summary/match-summary|access-date=18 February 2022|website=www.flashscore.co.uk|language=en-GB}}</ref>

=== Trabzonspor ===
On 4 July 2022, Trézéguet returned to the [[Süper Lig]] once again, joining reigning champions [[Trabzonspor]] on a permanent deal,<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=4 July 2022 |title=Trézéguet departs Aston Villa |url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/news/2022/july/04/tr-z-guet-departs-villa/ |access-date=4 July 2022 |website=Aston Villa Football Club}}</ref> for a transfer fee rumoured to be around £4.25M.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Townley |first=John |date=4 July 2022 |title=Aston Villa confirm Trezeguet transfer to Trabzonspor |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/trezeguet-aston-villa-transfer-breaking-24371172 |access-date=4 July 2022 |website=BirminghamLive |language=en}}</ref>

==== Loan to Al-Rayyan ====
In September 2024, Trézéguet joined Qatari side [[Al-Rayyan SC|Al-Rayyan]] by signing a one-season loan deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2024/09/03/mahmoud-trezeguet-joiuns-al-rayyan/ |title=OFFICIAL: Mahmoud Trezeguet joins Qatari side Al-Rayyan |publisher=KingFut |date=3 September 2024 }}</ref>

=== Return to Al Ahly ===
On 27 January 2025, it was announced that Trézéguet would return to his boyhood club [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] at the beginning of the [[2025–26 Egyptian Premier League|2025–26 season]] for a fee of €1.6 million, and on a 5-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ahmed |first=Saher |date=27 January 2025 |title=OFFICIAL: Al Ahly Secure Surprise Signing of Trezeguet |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2025/01/27/official-al-ahly-secure-surprise-signing-of-trezeguet/ |access-date=28 January 2025 |website=KingFut |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Mahmoud Trézéguet.jpg|thumb|upright|Trézéguet playing for [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]]]

Trézéguet represented Egypt at [[Egypt national under-20 football team|U20 level]], being named in the squad for the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]]. In his side's final group game, he scored the opening goal during a 2–0 victory over [[England U20|England]] on 20 June 2013, dribbling past two players before scoring. However, despite their victory, Egypt were eliminated in the group stage after finishing third.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Taylor bemoans 'worst performance' as England crash out |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jun/30/england-egypt-world-cup-defeat |access-date=23 May 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Rob Smyth |date=30 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2013/06/29/video-egypt-2-0-england-pharoahs-crash-out-of-the-u-20-world-cup/ |title=Egypt 2–0 England Pharaohs Crash Out of U-20 World Cup |website=KingFut.com |date=29 June 2014 |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref> Trézéguet made his debut with the [[Egypt national football team|senior national team]] on 30 August 2014 when he was 19 years and 10 months old in a 1–0 victory over [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]], before scoring his first senior goal in his third appearance during a 2–0 victory over [[Equatorial Guinea national football team|Equatorial Guinea]].<ref name="nft">{{NFT player|56709|access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

He was chosen by [[Héctor Cúper]] for the squad to play the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsAFCON/2017/254436.aspx |title=Egypt announce final squad for Africa Cup of Nations |website=Ahram Online |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> where he was a regular in the team's starting line-up; he helped his nation to reach the final of the tournament, losing 2–1 against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2017/feb/05/cameroon-v-egypt-afcon-2017-final-live-africa-cup-of-nations |title=Egypt 1–2 Cameroon: Afcon 2017 final – as it happened |first=Rob |last=Smyth |date=5 February 2017 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> He later credited Cúper for his improved form in the Cup of Nations and qualifying matches for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], where he came on as a substitute during his country's decisive qualifying victory over [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/match?gameId=464054 |title=Egypt 2–1 DR Congo |publisher=ESPN |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref> stating "He is a coach who respects those who exert efforts in training and matches."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/6/52/298290/Sports/National-Teams/Egypt-midfielder-Trezeguet-credits-Cuper-for-fine-.aspx |title=Egypt midfielder Trezeguet credits Cuper for fine form |publisher=Ahram Online |date=24 April 2018 |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, he was named in Egypt's preliminary [[Egypt national football team|squad]] for the 2018 World Cup in Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2018/05/13/egypt-announce-preliminary-squad-for-friendlies-ahead-of-world-cup/ |title=Egypt announce preliminary squad for friendlies ahead of World Cup |website=KingFut.com |author=Ali Ismail |date=13 May 2018 |access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> After being included in the final 23-man squad, he started all three of Egypt's group matches, defeats to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], as they were eliminated in the group stage.<ref name="nft"/>

Trézéguet returned from injury in time to be selected by [[Carlos Queiroz]] for the squad to play in the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] - which was taking place in January 2022, due to [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Oludare|first=Shina|date=30 December 2021|title=Egypt's Afcon 2021 squad confirmed: Queiroz names Liverpool's Salah and Arsenal's Elneny {{!}} Goal.com|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/egypt-afcon-2021-squad-confirmed-queiroz-names-liverpool/blt6ae97fff05be3081|access-date=27 January 2022|website=www.goal.com}}</ref> On 30 January 2022, he scored an extra-time winner in a 2–1 quarter-final victory over [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Egypt 2-1 Morocco: Trezeguet seals comeback win to set up AFCON semi-final against Cameroon|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/egypt-2-1-morocco-trezeguet-173907792.html|access-date=30 January 2022|website=uk.sports.yahoo.com|language=en-GB}}</ref> Trézéguet featured in all of Egypt's matches in the tournament as they were defeated by [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] on penalties in the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations Final|final]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=5 February 2022|title=Africa Cup of Nations final: Mane with winning penalty as Senegal beat Egypt on penalties|language=en-GB|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/59408846|access-date=8 February 2022}}</ref>

On 2 December 2025, Trézéguet was called up to the Egypt squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/egypt-name-final-28-man-squad-for-totalenergies-caf-afcon-2025-salah-leads-pharaohs-charge/|title=Egypt name final 28-man squad for TotalEnergies CAF AFCON 2025, Salah leads Pharaohs' charge|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=2 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

